  "description": "Account Data Deletion with Selective Purge & Confirmation Gate\n\nImplement a self-service data deletion flow that allows authenticated users to permanently and irreversibly remove some or all of their personal data from the system. The feature must prevent accidental deletion through an explicit text-confirmation gate and support granular selection of data categories to delete.\n\n---\n\nRequirements:\n\nUI & Flow\n- Add a \"Delete Account Data\" section in the user's Settings or Profile page, placed in a visually distinct Danger Zone area\n- Present a checklist of deletable data categories (all checked by default), allowing the user to deselect categories they wish to retain:\n  - Inbox / Emails (aggregated messages, attachments, embeddings)\n  - Kanban Boards, Columns & Cards (including labels, tags, comments, attachments)\n  - Meeting Transcripts & Intelligence (Krisp webhooks, key points, action items, speakers)\n  - Open Brain Memories (thought captures, vector embeddings, metadata)\n  - Pages / Notes (markdown content)\n  - Action Items (all lifecycle states — open, in_progress, completed, cancelled)\n  - Calendar Events\n  - Audit Logs & Activity History\n- Surface a clear summary line before confirmation, e.g. \"You are about to permanently delete: Inbox, Kanban, Meetings (3 categories selected)\"\n- Require the user to type the exact phrase DELETE MY DATA (case-insensitive acceptable, but must match) into a text input field before the destructive action is enabled\n- Confirm button must remain disabled until the typed phrase matches exactly\n- On submit, show an inline loading state and prevent duplicate submissions\n\nBackend & Data Integrity\n- Implement a single API endpoint (e.g., POST /api/account/delete-data) that accepts the list of selected categories and the confirmation phrase, and re-validates the phrase server-side before executing\n- All deletions must cascade correctly — remove child records (embeddings, action items linked to meetings, cards within columns, etc.) before parent records to avoid foreign key violations\n- Vector embeddings stored in pgvector must be explicitly deleted alongside their parent records\n- Soft-deleted records (trash) must also be purged within the selected categories\n- Wrap all deletions in a database transaction — if any category deletion fails, roll back the entire operation and return a descriptive error\n- Log the deletion event to the audit trail before executing (record which categories, timestamp, user ID) so a pre-deletion record exists even if the user later deletes audit logs separately\n\nPost-Deletion Behavior\n- If the user deletes all categories (full wipe), invalidate their session and redirect to a confirmation screen with a message such as \"Your data has been permanently deleted\"\n- If a partial deletion is performed, reload the affected views and surfaces to reflect the removed data without stale state\n- Send a transactional confirmation email via Resend summarising which categories were deleted and at what time\n\nEdge Cases & Constraints\n- Deletion must be scoped strictly to the authenticated user's own data — no cross-user access possible at the query level\n- Handle the case where a category has no data gracefully (skip silently, do not surface as an error)\n- If a third-party sync (Gmail push, Microsoft Graph subscription) is active, unsubscribe from those webhooks before deleting the associated email data to prevent orphaned subscriptions\n- Rate-limit the endpoint to prevent abuse (e.g., max 3 deletion requests per user per hour)\n- Do not expose the deletion endpoint to API key holders — require a valid NextAuth session only",
