ked to meetings, cards within columns, etc.) before parent records to avoid foreign key violations\n- Vector embeddings stored in pgvector must be explicitly deleted alongside their parent records\n- Soft-deleted records (trash) must also be purged within the selected categories\n- Wrap all deletions in a database transaction — if any category deletion fails, roll back the entire operation and return a descriptive error\n- Log the deletion event to the audit trail before executing (record which categories, timestamp, user ID) so a pre-deletion record exists even if the user later deletes audit logs separately\n\nPost-Deletion Behavior\n- If the user deletes all categories (full wipe), invalidate their session and redirect to a confirmation screen with a message such as \"Your data has been permanently deleted\"\n- If a partial deletion is performed, reload the affected views and surfaces to reflect the removed data without stale state\n- Send a transactional confirmation email via Resend summarising which categories were deleted and at what time\n\nEdge Cases & Constraints\n- Deletion must be scoped strictly to the authenticated user's own data — no cross-user access possible at the query level\n- Handle the case where a category has no data gracefully (skip silently, do not surface as an error)\n- If a third-party sync (Gmail push, Microsoft Graph subscription) is active, unsubscribe from those webhooks before deleting the associated email data to prevent orphaned subscriptions\n- Rate-limit the endpoint to prevent abuse (e.g., max 3 deletion requests per user per hour)\n- Do not expose the deletion endpoint to API key holders — require a valid NextAuth session only",
